Implement the private `collect/2` helper used by `search/2` and `words/1`.

It performs a depth-first traversal of the trie starting from a given node and
gathers every complete word found beneath it. The function takes two arguments:
a trie node (a map of the shape `%{end_of_word: boolean, children: %{char => node}}`)
and an accumulator string `acc` representing the path of characters walked so far
to reach this node.

Behaviour:

- If the current node has `end_of_word: true`, then `acc` is itself a complete
  word and must be included in the result. Start the local result as `[acc]` in
  that case, or `[]` otherwise.
- Then recurse into every child: for each `{char, child}` pair in the node's
  `children` map, call `collect/2` on `child` with the accumulator extended by
  that character (`acc <> char`), and combine each child's collected words with
  the words gathered so far.
- Return a flat list of all complete words beneath `node` (in any order — callers
  sort the result themselves).

The function does not sort; ordering is handled by `search/2` and `words/1`.

